00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:23.780
So misconceptions.

00:00:26.530 --> 00:00:30.550
So misconceptions, alternative
conceptions, understanding the

00:00:30.550 --> 00:00:34.740
student view of the world,
why is that important?

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:40.460
Well one of the best ways to
introduce the importance of

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:42.860
the idea is a story.

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:56.660
Now I'm not 100% sure the story
is true, but it's so

00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:58.960
good that it ought to be
true even if it isn't.

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:00.530
I think it is actually true.

00:01:00.530 --> 00:01:08.320
So this was two, let's say
physics, TAs, physics grad

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:11.550
students, who were in
a philosophy class.

00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:15.370
And the teacher in the
philosophy class said well--

00:01:15.370 --> 00:01:18.140
they were talking about things
being relative, and morals

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:23.650
being relatives, and relativity
in philosophy--

00:01:23.650 --> 00:01:28.180
as an example of relativity,
and things being relative

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:33.210
depending on the situation, if
you drop a pencil on the

00:01:33.210 --> 00:01:35.430
Earth, it will fall
to the ground.

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:37.800
But if you drop the pencil
on the moon, it

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:38.720
won't fall to the ground.

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:40.270
It will just float.

00:01:40.270 --> 00:01:43.650
And so most of the people in
the class just nodded,

00:01:43.650 --> 00:01:46.320
basically thinking, oh that's
a good example.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:50.520
But the two physicists in the
class were a bit shocked and

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:53.040
said well wait a minute,
wait a minute.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:55.720
That can't be true.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:57.840
Surely, something
is wrong here.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:01:58.640
So they raised their hand.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:00.810
They said, well wait a minute.

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:05.570
If you drop a pencil on the
moon, surely it's going to

00:02:05.570 --> 00:02:08.620
fall to the ground, to the
ground of the moon.

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:11.730
And the other people in
the class said, no,

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:13.150
no, that's not right.

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:13.880
That's not right.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:18.440
So they thought, OK, well we
have some way of convincing

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:20.700
them that the pencil's
not going to float.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:23.590
And they said, OK well you all
saw the pictures of the

00:02:23.590 --> 00:02:25.190
astronauts walking on
the moon, right?

00:02:25.190 --> 00:02:27.100
And they said, oh yeah.

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:32.860
Well, when the astronauts walk,
did they just float

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:34.580
away, or did they stay
on the moon?

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:36.670
Oh, they stayed on the moon.

00:02:36.670 --> 00:02:38.980
Well, how'd that happen?

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:40.780
They thought, oh we
have them now.

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:41.790
And what was the response?

00:02:41.790 --> 00:02:43.870
The response was, oh, well
that was because the

00:02:43.870 --> 00:02:45.470
astronauts were wearing
heavy boots.

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:52.930
So here was a chance to do a bit
of educational research.

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:54.200
So they thought, oh my god.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:56.790
Maybe is this just this class?

00:02:56.790 --> 00:02:58.390
Let's actually do a survey.

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:00.590
So they took out the university
phone directory and

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:02.370
just randomly dialed people.

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:08.090
And they called them up and
said, OK if you drop a pencil

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:10.020
on the moon, will
it float away or

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:11.260
will fall to the ground?

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:13.990
And most of the people said,
it's going to float away.

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:17.080
So then they said, oh yeah, but
what about the astronauts?

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:17.860
And they gave them the
whole thing about

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:19.050
the astronauts again.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:22.290
And about half of the people
said, oh yeah, that's because

00:03:22.290 --> 00:03:25.270
the astronauts were wearing
heavy boots.

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:27.870
So again, they were shocked
and flabbergasted.

00:03:27.870 --> 00:03:31.790
And I think that reaction is
a very healthy reaction.

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:36.110
But what it shows is
that the students--

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:38.900
so in this case they weren't
officially their students--

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:39.950
but students--

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:41.470
they could easily be
your students--

00:03:41.470 --> 00:03:45.240
can have a very different view
of the world, of the physical

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:47.090
world, than you have.

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:52.300
And if that's true, that means
that as you're teaching them,

00:03:52.300 --> 00:03:55.530
what you're teaching is actually
being interpreted in

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:58.740
this completely different way.

00:03:58.740 --> 00:04:00.190
I think Goethe said that--

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:02.630
he said that mathematicians,
or maybe it was Frenchmen.

00:04:02.630 --> 00:04:04.410
It was either Frenchmen
or mathematicians.

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:06.260
Maybe it was mathematicians.

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:08.380
They have their own language,
and everything you tell them,

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:10.540
they first translate into their
own language, and only

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:12.240
then do they understand it.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:13.570
So that's the same thing.

00:04:13.570 --> 00:04:16.390
The students are translating the
things you're saying into

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:17.600
their own language.

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:19.880
But to understand what they're
translating into, you have to

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:21.800
know what their language is.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:24.640
So in other words, you have
to understand not just the

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:28.970
misconceptions, but in general
the conceptions that students

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:31.420
have, so that you can actually
plan your teaching.

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:33.948
And here is a diagram
to illustrate that.

00:04:56.070 --> 00:05:07.040
So this is a model of teaching
to see where all

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:08.600
the pieces fit in.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.630
So here, this is the system,
which is how students think.

00:05:16.550 --> 00:05:22.570
This is the output, which is
what students can do after

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:24.490
they go through our teaching.

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:30.850
And this is the input, which
is what we do, what kind of

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.200
classroom structure we set up,
what assignments we do.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:37.030
And by this, I mean how students
think individually

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:39.570
and collectively, how students
work together, as well.

00:05:39.570 --> 00:05:43.030
So generally speaking
the way--

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:45.040
so this is the system.

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:48.450
And call this the result.

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:52.470
And this is the teaching.

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:54.490
Our problem is trying to figure
out the teaching.

00:06:04.270 --> 00:06:05.540
And how do you figure
out the teaching?

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:09.140
Well you start with figuring
out what result you want.

00:06:09.140 --> 00:06:10.850
What do you want students
to be able to do?

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:13.200
What is your goal
for the class?

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:16.600
And then you have to run it
back through the system.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:22.310
Right so you figure out the
result, and you run it through

00:06:22.310 --> 00:06:24.190
the inverse of s.

00:06:24.190 --> 00:06:25.970
And then there's
your teaching.

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:28.170
That's the teaching equation
let's call it.

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:39.420
Now those of you from
engineering fields know that

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:42.480
basically the only thing
you can do anything

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:44.560
with is linear systems.

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:47.390
And unfortunately anything
that's even slightly non

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.450
linear basically is a bag of
tricks, and there's nothing

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:49.780
you can do.

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:51.340
And you're just hosed.

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:54.580
Well unfortunately this system
is incredibly non-linear.

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:58.070
So it's probably kind of hard to
work out s inverse, even if

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:00.180
you can work out r.

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:03.060
But it's hard, but it doesn't
mean you can't start.

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:06.220
And a necessary condition for
even doing anything in this

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:09.980
direction is you have to
know what is in s,

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:11.340
how do students think.

00:07:11.340 --> 00:07:14.440
Another necessary condition
is you need to work out r.

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:16.180
And that's actually
something--

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:17.670
what is the result you want?

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:19.270
So that we're going to
talk about in the

00:07:19.270 --> 00:07:20.710
session on course design.

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:23.640
That's something that's often
forgotten in teaching, and

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:25.090
it's fundamentally important.

00:07:25.090 --> 00:07:28.060
That if you don't plan your
goals, if you don't plan where

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:31.750
you want to go, your chance of
getting there is pretty low.

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:33.780
So assume you've done that.

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:36.100
The next thing you want to do is
you want to understand how

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:39.000
students think, so that you
can plan your teaching to

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.450
reach them, in other words,
so you have some chance of

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:42.980
working out s inverse.

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:44.970
Now you can't actually write
down some equation for s

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:47.360
inverse, but you can invert
it mentally in your head.

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:50.310
And a necessary condition for
doing that is to understand s.

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:52.700
So you want to understand where
students are coming

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:57.710
from, so that you
can work out t.

00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:02.700
So that's the signals and
systems model of teaching.

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:08.820
Now, an example again to show
the importance of doing that

00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:11.110
and what happens if you don't
actually understand where the

00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:14.430
student's are is yet another
example from freshman physics.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:16.710
I'll leave this here.

00:08:16.710 --> 00:08:20.210
So this is one of the examples
from the readings.

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:22.050
So not everyone may have
read that reading.

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:24.450
It's the reading by Reif.

00:08:24.450 --> 00:08:25.700
And it's this problem.

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:37.890
So this is a pendulum at
five points in its arc.

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:39.549
So these are the endpoints.

00:08:39.549 --> 00:08:43.929
And the question people were
asked was to draw the

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:47.340
acceleration vector at
these five locations.

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:49.350
So what's the acceleration
right here, here,

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:52.490
here, here, and here?

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:56.490
So I'm not so interested in what
the actual answer is as

00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:59.700
so much as how people
did on this.

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:01.850
So this is actually
really shocking.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:09.660
So of students in intro
physics who've had

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:10.380
acceleration--

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:11.630
so they'd done acceleration--

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:22.760
zero out of 124 students
could do that problem.

00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:34.800
So that's 0%.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:41.580
So of grad TAs, it was 15%.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:46.130
So these are grad TAs in physics
who TA that course.

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:47.550
And PhD students--

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:54.320
so was PhD students on their
qualifying exam.

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:55.570
It went up to 22%.

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:04.320
OK so now this is a
fundamentally important idea,

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:06.680
acceleration.

00:10:06.680 --> 00:10:09.710
But you'd expect PhD students
on their qualifying

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:11.930
exam to be at 100%.

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:15.530
And you'd like the TAs in the
course to be at 100%.

00:10:15.530 --> 00:10:17.860
Because there's no chance of
them teaching the students an

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:20.020
idea that they themselves
don't understand.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:22.600
As Polya said, there's no
method of teaching yet

00:10:22.600 --> 00:10:26.700
invented that will allow the
students to understand what

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:28.450
their teacher does not.

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:29.220
And that's true.

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:33.000
There's no amount of sort of
trickery with style and things

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.810
you can do to convey
an understanding

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:37.450
that you don't have.

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:41.710
So this is a very shocking
number to me.

00:10:41.710 --> 00:10:42.440
And--

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:42.740
AUDIENCE: Who said that?

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:43.300
PROFESSOR: Pardon?

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:44.260
AUDIENCE: Who said that?

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:45.510
PROFESSOR: George Polya.

00:10:50.190 --> 00:10:54.300
So Polya was a great mathematics
teacher from

00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:58.020
Hungary and then eventually
at Stanford.

00:10:58.020 --> 00:10:59.170
And he's written--

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:02.870
I'll put references to his
books on the website.

00:11:02.870 --> 00:11:04.700
But they are some of the
best books on math

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:06.470
teaching ever written.

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:08.700
And so he said that in
one of his books.

00:11:08.700 --> 00:11:12.110
And it's I think very true.

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:17.530
So what this example shows is
that, a, the teachers didn't

00:11:17.530 --> 00:11:18.250
understand it.

00:11:18.250 --> 00:11:21.590
But that really fundamental
ideas can be completely

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:24.230
skipped over for years
and years and years.

00:11:28.190 --> 00:11:29.120
Yes, [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:31.454
AUDIENCE: It's a special
example of some vague,

00:11:31.454 --> 00:11:32.897
conceptually difficult
problem.

00:11:32.897 --> 00:11:35.783
I'm just wondering-- so
I read the article.

00:11:35.783 --> 00:11:38.030
Did they focus on how to
figure the answer out?

00:11:38.030 --> 00:11:40.980
Because a lot of physics
majors don't.

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:42.500
PROFESSOR: OK, so the
question is, how

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:44.700
difficult is this problem?

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:48.760
It's an interesting problem,
because it's difficult if you

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:51.450
try to do it by just blasting
out the equations.

00:11:51.450 --> 00:11:54.930
So they actually asked
a bunch of faculty

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.830
members the same question.

00:11:56.830 --> 00:11:59.280
And one of them just got
completely tangled in knots,

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:01.830
physics faculty, trying to write
out the differential

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:03.390
equation and figure
out what the

00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:05.690
acceleration is by brute force.

00:12:05.690 --> 00:12:07.440
So yeah, it is hard if
you do it that way.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:09.770
But if you actually
understand--

00:12:09.770 --> 00:12:10.930
I'll show you--

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:14.410
what the acceleration means,
then it's no problem.

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:17.670
So for example, here, the
thing isn't moving.

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:19.080
So it has v equals zero.

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:22.440
But, what velocity is it going
to have just a bit later.

00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:24.190
Well it's going to be
going that way.

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:25.840
So that means acceleration
is that way.

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:28.640
AUDIENCE: But were they given
enough time to do this, to do

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:29.690
this thinking problem?

00:12:29.690 --> 00:12:32.360
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so they were
given quite a while.

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:34.380
I think it was--

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:36.640
when the study on the faculty
members, I think it was a big

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:37.715
long think aloud protocol.

00:12:37.715 --> 00:12:39.350
So they were given like
half an hour.

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:42.190
In fact, the time is
what hurt them.

00:12:42.190 --> 00:12:45.210
Because they all thought,
oh I have so much time.

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:48.080
I'm going to just blast
it out with equations.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:49.780
And if you were only given one
minute, you might have

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:50.850
actually had a chance.

00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:52.270
Because you realized, oh I
have to think about this

00:12:52.270 --> 00:12:54.260
intuitively.

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:57.060
So here, same thing
by symmetry.

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:58.240
And then this one is hard.

00:12:58.240 --> 00:12:58.940
And this one is hard.

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:01.280
But this one right at the
center is much easier.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.930
So this one catches
a lot of people.

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:08.240
But here it's moving in a
circle, and it's at its

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:09.800
maximum speed.

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:11.880
So here it's moving at
its maximum speed.

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:15.510
So it's not going to be going
faster that way or that way.

00:13:15.510 --> 00:13:17.950
So its speed is actually at a
max, which means there's no

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:18.930
change in speed.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:19.910
So you're not going to get any

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:21.430
acceleration in that direction.

00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:23.100
But because it's moving
in a circle,

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:25.090
somebody's yanking it upwards.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:27.330
So it has to be accelerating
upwards to move in a circle,

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:28.880
because it was going this way.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:30.800
And then later, it's
going that way.

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:32.780
So it has to be accelerating
upwards.

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:40.050
So there's an acceleration
vector upwards, like that.

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:44.110
So this is a bit exaggerated.

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:46.460
It's generally not that big.

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:48.700
And then the question is, with
these guys, well it's just

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:49.600
interpolation.

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:51.400
It's somewhere between
that and that.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:53.310
So it's going to be something
like that and something like

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:56.400
that, depending on where
exactly they are.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:14:01.460
But this is the one that tripped
up a lot of people.

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:03.730
And in fact, a lot of people
got tripped up because they

00:14:03.730 --> 00:14:09.110
memorize the following thing,
which is an object in simple

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:11.430
harmonic motion has no
acceleration at the

00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:12.980
equilibrium point.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:14.780
And that's true, except
this isn't a

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:15.750
simple harmonic motion.

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:16.310
It's almost.

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:17.020
But it's a pendulum.

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:18.400
It's not a pure spring.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:19.680
So it has circular motion.

00:14:19.680 --> 00:14:21.890
So if you reason about it
from the motion, it's

00:14:21.890 --> 00:14:22.990
actually very quick.

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:25.020
But if you try to blast it out
with equations, you're

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:26.270
basically hosed.

00:14:29.790 --> 00:14:35.560
So I wanted to check also, how
deep are these misconceptions?

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:39.370
So I actually did a survey of
students in Cambridge in the

00:14:39.370 --> 00:14:40.940
physics major.

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:44.850
And so one of the questions I
asked them was the following--

00:14:44.850 --> 00:14:48.670
so I made a survey of
nine questions.

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:51.865
And I wanted to see how they
reasoned intuitively on these

00:14:51.865 --> 00:14:52.560
nine questions.

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:54.690
And to force intuitive
reasoning, I only gave a few

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:56.900
minutes to get around
the problem.

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:59.960
So they knew that basically
writing out a bunch of

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:01.810
equations wasn't going to help,
because you had no time

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:03.143
to actually write
them all out.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.230
So the question was, which
is going to go

00:15:19.230 --> 00:15:21.010
faster down the plane?

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:24.840
So these are two identical
planes, inclined planes with

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:25.950
angle alpha.

00:15:25.950 --> 00:15:29.290
And there is either going to be
a disk like a coin rolling

00:15:29.290 --> 00:15:32.560
down the plane, or a ring, like
somebody's wedding ring

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:33.760
rolling down the plane.

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:36.240
And the question is, which goes
faster, or which has a

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:37.850
bigger acceleration.

00:15:37.850 --> 00:15:43.960
So this we'll call the hoop,
and this is the disk.

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:46.626
And they're going down
the same angle.

00:15:46.626 --> 00:15:48.640
AUDIENCE: The mass
is the same.

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:50.190
PROFESSOR: I didn't say that.

00:15:50.190 --> 00:15:51.690
The question is, is
the mass the same?

00:15:51.690 --> 00:15:53.390
So I'm going to give
you that choice.

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:56.690
So the question is, which
goes faster in

00:15:56.690 --> 00:15:58.310
acceleration or velocity?

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:00.821
So the choices were the hoop--

00:16:16.230 --> 00:16:19.170
So to answer the question about
mass, one of the choices

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:20.420
is that it depends on mass.

00:16:24.950 --> 00:16:33.630
Depends upon radius or
depends on alpha.

00:16:33.630 --> 00:16:36.820
So it could depend on the mass,
the radius, or on alpha.

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:38.080
It could be the same.

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:39.100
The disk could be faster.

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:41.030
Or the hoop could be faster.

00:16:41.030 --> 00:16:43.015
OK, so just for fun--

00:16:43.015 --> 00:16:45.090
and I realize this is not
a physics class--

00:16:45.090 --> 00:16:47.450
but it's fun to actually try to
guess the answer to this,

00:16:47.450 --> 00:16:49.030
even if you're not
a physicist.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:55.190
So choose A, B, C, D, E,
or F in cooperation

00:16:55.190 --> 00:16:57.880
with one or two neighbors.

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:01.460
And then I'll talk about my
analysis of this problem.

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:11.780
OK, take another 30 seconds
and collect a vote.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:15.849
Again, it doesn't really matter
whether you get it

00:17:15.849 --> 00:17:16.569
right or not.

00:17:16.569 --> 00:17:19.540
I just want you to think about
it, so you realize it is a

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:20.790
subtle question.

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:30.655
OK, so who votes for the
hoop being faster?

00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:35.670
Who votes for the disk
being faster?

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:40.780
Who votes that they're
the same?

00:17:43.867 --> 00:17:47.280
That it depends on the mass,
you'd like to know the mass?

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:49.180
Fair enough.

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:50.430
That you'd like to
know the radius?

00:17:53.870 --> 00:17:54.790
Maybe 12.

00:17:54.790 --> 00:17:57.880
That you'd like to know the
inclined plane angle?

00:17:57.880 --> 00:17:59.722
Nobody like that one, OK.

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:11.370
And now who's sure
of their answer.

00:18:11.370 --> 00:18:15.260
OK, so that's a much
lower number.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:19.995
So now I can show you what
numbers came up when I asked

00:18:19.995 --> 00:18:22.610
the students this.

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:26.000
So this was 11%.

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:31.980
35%.

00:18:31.980 --> 00:18:33.850
13%.

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:38.310
This one is 11% as well.

00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:39.775
Radius was 26%.

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:44.300
And 3%.

00:18:44.300 --> 00:18:49.320
So kind of similar, kind of
similar to your percentages.

00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:53.080
And again, only about a third
of the people were sure of

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:54.720
their answer.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:57.400
OK, so why is this
interesting?

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:00.560
Well first of all, all the
students had the technical

00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:03.030
knowledge to do the problem.

00:19:03.030 --> 00:19:05.670
These were all physics majors in
various years, one through

00:19:05.670 --> 00:19:08.310
four, so freshman
through senior.

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:11.840
But the freshman had seen the
material to actually do this

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:15.090
and calculate it if
they need to.

00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:18.250
So now this problem illustrates
well first of all

00:19:18.250 --> 00:19:22.120
that even an intuitive question
like this can

00:19:22.120 --> 00:19:23.780
actually trip people up, even
if they've done all the

00:19:23.780 --> 00:19:25.410
calculations.

00:19:25.410 --> 00:19:27.990
So the question is, how
are they reasoning?

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:31.510
Now in Cambridge I had the
advantage of also doing

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:34.620
tutorials, because that's how
half the teaching goes.

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:38.460
So in tutorials I actually
I set this problem for my

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:40.750
students, and I got a chance
to talk to them about it.

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:43.580
So I got to figure out, how are
they reasoning about it?

00:19:43.580 --> 00:19:46.410
So I asked them, well what do
you think is going to happen?

00:19:46.410 --> 00:19:48.680
And then please explain why,
more than you can get just

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:49.990
from multiple choice.

00:19:49.990 --> 00:19:52.960
And the answers were
very revealing.

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:57.460
What they said was, many of
them said, well, just as

00:19:57.460 --> 00:20:01.740
heavier objects fall faster,
so should heavier

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:03.860
objects roll faster.

00:20:03.860 --> 00:20:08.890
So that was basically to justify
they wanted to know

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:11.590
either the radius or the mass,
because that would affect the

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:13.580
mass, and that would also
affect the mass.

00:20:13.580 --> 00:20:15.900
So, let me put that up again,
because that's a really

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:17.150
interesting statement.

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:40.830
So actually what I call this,
this is like the American

00:20:40.830 --> 00:20:43.040
theory of the British accent.

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:45.160
Some of you know my explanation
of that.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:49.020
So the American theory of the
British accent is that if you

00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:51.630
go to an English person and you
step on their feet in the

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:55.340
middle of the nigh, they'll
actually cry out in an

00:20:55.340 --> 00:20:57.130
American accent.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:21:00.080
Which is to say that the
American, sort of folk theory

00:21:00.080 --> 00:21:02.810
of the British accent is that
the British accent is a fake

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:06.110
that people just put on, and
in moments of stress they

00:21:06.110 --> 00:21:08.220
forget to do the put on act.

00:21:08.220 --> 00:21:09.920
OK, so now why do
I bring that up?

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:12.450
Well because it's
very similar.

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:14.780
So if you ask the students--

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:16.310
suppose you didn't tell
them this question

00:21:16.310 --> 00:21:17.210
about inclined planes.

00:21:17.210 --> 00:21:19.910
You just say, do heavier
objects fall faster?

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:22.090
You don't know about air
resistance or anything.

00:21:22.090 --> 00:21:24.690
They say, oh no definitely
not.

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:27.440
Galileo showed that.

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:31.340
But what this shows is that in
a new situation, in other

00:21:31.340 --> 00:21:34.840
words where they don't have
their automatic reactions, all

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:38.360
of a sudden the folk theory
comes out again.

00:21:38.360 --> 00:21:40.960
They really do think heavier
objects fall faster.

00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:43.160
Right, so how can you reconcile
that with if you ask

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:44.520
them, they'll say
no they don't?

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:48.590
Well that's because they had so
much experience with every

00:21:48.590 --> 00:21:50.940
time they said that, someone
said, whack.

00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:52.230
Heavier objects fall
at the same speed.

00:21:52.230 --> 00:21:54.090
Galileo showed that, Leaning
Tower of Pisa.

00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:57.790
So it becomes this linguistic
string which hasn't actually

00:21:57.790 --> 00:22:02.080
been incorporated into their way
of thinking about how the

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:03.470
world works.

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:06.420
They think force is related
to velocity, heavier

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:07.830
objects fall faster.

00:22:07.830 --> 00:22:10.430
And to get that to come out,
you have to, for example,

00:22:10.430 --> 00:22:13.020
equivalent to stepping on them
in the middle of a night,

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:14.580
surprising them.

00:22:14.580 --> 00:22:17.970
So you surprise them with a
completely new context, which

00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:19.610
is the rolling.

00:22:19.610 --> 00:22:21.600
Rolling, they haven't thought
much about rolling.

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:24.400
So all of a sudden, they're now
thinking about rolling.

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:27.840
And they're not thinking about
all the policing rules that

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:30.300
they were told about what
happens to heavier objects.

00:22:30.300 --> 00:22:32.760
And so now their true way of
looking at the world comes

00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:36.760
out, which is that heavier
objects fall faster.

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:40.180
So again, if you don't realize
that that's what they're

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:44.640
doing, your teaching is going
to be completely pointless.

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:48.600
And what's going to happen is
the following, which is that

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:51.900
here are two models.

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:54.470
The students will develop
two models of the

00:22:54.470 --> 00:22:55.640
world in their mind.

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:58.190
One let's call it the
school model.

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.320
And another is their
intuitive model.

00:23:06.750 --> 00:23:10.370
And let's say they start out a
bit different from each other.

00:23:10.370 --> 00:23:13.660
And now you do a whole bunch
more teaching, and you don't

00:23:13.660 --> 00:23:16.060
take account of the fact that
this belongs in their

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:17.400
intuitive model.

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:20.200
And you teach a bunch of stuff
about rolling down the plane.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:22.060
You do it with a bunch
of equations.

00:23:22.060 --> 00:23:26.110
By the way, I should tell you
what the right answer is.

00:23:26.110 --> 00:23:29.280
The right answer is this one.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:32.140
It actually doesn't matter how
heavy they are, because it's a

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:34.110
gravitation problem.

00:23:34.110 --> 00:23:36.680
But suppose you just
calculated it out.

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:38.050
Well what have you done?

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:41.760
You've overlaid on top of this,
you've put in-- so this

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:44.380
is their intuitive model.

00:23:44.380 --> 00:23:46.060
You've done a whole bunch
of calculations

00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:47.400
which contradict it.

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:50.800
And the two models diverge
farther and

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:52.030
farther from each other.

00:23:52.030 --> 00:23:55.330
So now next time they have to
solve a problem, they have to

00:23:55.330 --> 00:23:57.230
decide whether I'm going to use
the school model or the

00:23:57.230 --> 00:23:58.540
intuitive model.

00:23:58.540 --> 00:24:00.380
And they learn, OK, well
the intuitive model

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:00.870
doesn't work very well.

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:01.830
Let me use the school model.

00:24:01.830 --> 00:24:04.860
So the school model basically
keeps diverging.

00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:07.610
And the intuitive model and the
school model never meet

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:10.930
again, which means that they
can't use their intuition for

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:12.720
solving any of the problems you
give them, or that they're

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:13.790
going to solve later.

00:24:13.790 --> 00:24:17.760
So that is an educational
tragedy.

00:24:17.760 --> 00:24:30.900
So the divergence, and in my
view, that is the fundamental

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:33.470
reason why most teaching
produces no

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:35.240
results a year later.

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:38.650
Because what you've done is
you've developed the school

00:24:38.650 --> 00:24:41.270
model, the symbolic crunching,
whatever it may be.

00:24:41.270 --> 00:24:43.635
But you haven't actually yanked
the intuitive model and

00:24:43.635 --> 00:24:44.860
the school model together.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:47.690
You need to actually work on
bringing them together.

00:24:47.690 --> 00:24:51.410
So now the natural question
is, how do you do that?

00:24:51.410 --> 00:24:53.370
So let me give you another
example of a similar

00:24:53.370 --> 00:24:56.500
misconception and a way of
yanking the two together.

00:24:56.500 --> 00:24:57.040
Yes, question.

00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:58.378
AUDIENCE: Would you mind
explaining why

00:24:58.378 --> 00:24:59.720
the disk rolls faster?

00:24:59.720 --> 00:25:02.430
PROFESSOR: Oh, yeah,
why is it the disk?

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:05.390
Yeah, sure.

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:08.390
So first of all, why doesn't
it depend on

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:10.220
let's say the mass?

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:13.690
So that's one thing to
clear up right away.

00:25:13.690 --> 00:25:17.470
And one way to reason about
that, maybe the best way in a

00:25:17.470 --> 00:25:19.770
physics class is to do
it by dimensions.

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:22.970
But another way is the following
thought experiment.

00:25:22.970 --> 00:25:26.020
Which is, suppose I
have two disks--

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:27.520
let's see, I might
be poor today.

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:29.870
I only have one disk
in my pocket.

00:25:29.870 --> 00:25:32.370
Well here's two disks.

00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:33.930
The chalk is also a disk.

00:25:33.930 --> 00:25:36.940
So now, suppose I have one piece
of chalk, and I want to

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:38.690
roll it down the
incline plane.

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:41.570
And now I ask about a second
piece of chalk.

00:25:41.570 --> 00:25:42.900
Let's say they're identical
pieces of chalk.

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:44.790
They're both going to go
at the same speed.

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:48.550
OK, so now suppose I stick a bit
of glue on this chalk and

00:25:48.550 --> 00:25:50.480
that chalk, and I stick
them together.

00:25:50.480 --> 00:25:53.110
They're going to go, again, at
the same speed, as if the glue

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:53.690
weren't there.

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:55.170
Because the glue isn't
being stressed.

00:25:55.170 --> 00:25:56.430
They're just moving
identically.

00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:58.820
So what I've shown by that
experiment is that a heavy

00:25:58.820 --> 00:26:00.850
piece of chalk moves
just the same as a

00:26:00.850 --> 00:26:01.970
light piece of chalk.

00:26:01.970 --> 00:26:05.240
So it's quite plausible from
that reasoning that mass

00:26:05.240 --> 00:26:07.110
doesn't matter.

00:26:07.110 --> 00:26:08.530
Why doesn't radius matter?

00:26:08.530 --> 00:26:11.240
Well you could do a couple of
scaling arguments to show that

00:26:11.240 --> 00:26:14.520
the extra torque you get from
being bigger is exactly

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:19.570
canceled out by the extra mass
because you're bigger.

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:22.970
So the radius doesn't matter.

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:24.080
Mass and radius don't matter.

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:26.710
So then it's just a question
of shape, which is a

00:26:26.710 --> 00:26:28.200
dimensionalist thing.

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:32.300
And what it is intuitively is
how concentrated is the mass

00:26:32.300 --> 00:26:34.700
near the center versus
near the edge.

00:26:34.700 --> 00:26:40.010
So suppose I actually made a
extreme version of the hoop.

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:42.450
And actually I did this for
the students in Cambridge.

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:43.640
We manufactured--

00:26:43.640 --> 00:26:45.820
and you could actually
imagine what it is.

00:26:45.820 --> 00:26:47.850
So imagine this were
hollow inside.

00:26:47.850 --> 00:26:49.960
That would be your ring
or your hoop.

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:52.270
Well can you make anything that
would move even slower?

00:26:52.270 --> 00:26:54.320
Because I'm planning the hoop
moves slower than the disk.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:59.170
Yes, what you do is you put
giant ears on the thing.

00:26:59.170 --> 00:27:02.710
So it rolls like those dumbbell
things you do for

00:27:02.710 --> 00:27:03.580
weightlifting.

00:27:03.580 --> 00:27:07.840
So it rolls on this radius, but
it has these giant ears.

00:27:07.840 --> 00:27:10.450
Well it's just going to move so
slowly, because it's just

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:12.850
being yanked by this
really weak force.

00:27:12.850 --> 00:27:15.320
And it has to accelerate
this giant mass.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:15.830
No chance.

00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:16.690
So it moves really slow.

00:27:16.690 --> 00:27:19.600
In fact, that thing it can take
20 seconds to go down a

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:21.750
meter long inclined plane.

00:27:21.750 --> 00:27:23.350
So that's an extreme version.

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:29.490
So it rolls on this, and
this is these big ears.

00:27:29.490 --> 00:27:30.580
So that's really slow.

00:27:30.580 --> 00:27:31.560
That's medium slow.

00:27:31.560 --> 00:27:32.910
And that's faster.

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:34.870
And if you put all the mass
right at the center, it would

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:37.290
be even faster, because the
rolling wouldn't suck up any

00:27:37.290 --> 00:27:39.790
of the energy.

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:41.040
So that's the intuitive
explanation.

00:27:45.470 --> 00:27:49.400
OK so now an example of a
question showing a kind of

00:27:49.400 --> 00:27:53.000
similar misconception, a
related misconception.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.620
But I'm going to show it to you
to illustrate what you can

00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:58.030
do about this.

00:27:58.030 --> 00:27:58.910
So what can you do about it?

00:27:58.910 --> 00:28:00.780
So the question is
the following.

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:16.820
So that's a steel ball, which I
have in my hand, and I drop

00:28:16.820 --> 00:28:19.520
on a steel table, say from
a meter up high.

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:20.850
Forget about air resistance.

00:28:20.850 --> 00:28:22.780
It bounces off the
steel table.

00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:23.930
And the question is
I'm interested in

00:28:23.930 --> 00:28:25.670
the forces on it.

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:26.540
So what are the forces.

00:28:26.540 --> 00:28:29.100
So here's my table.

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:49.620
So while it's falling, I'm
interested in the forces on it

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:52.190
at three different points
in its flight.

00:28:52.190 --> 00:28:53.550
First while it's falling.

00:28:53.550 --> 00:28:56.110
I've let it go, and
it hasn't yet hit.

00:28:56.110 --> 00:28:59.910
At the instant that it's
stationary during its bounce.

00:28:59.910 --> 00:29:02.780
And while it's rising.

00:29:02.780 --> 00:29:06.070
So when you ask the students
this-- and I've done this

00:29:06.070 --> 00:29:07.450
several times--

00:29:07.450 --> 00:29:10.650
mostly they know it's
just gravity while

00:29:10.650 --> 00:29:16.590
it's falling, mg.

00:29:16.590 --> 00:29:19.830
So if you actually use this
question, don't ask--

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:22.200
this is chronologically next,
but don't ask that next.

00:29:22.200 --> 00:29:25.090
Ask this one, when
it's rising.

00:29:25.090 --> 00:29:26.860
And what you'll find--

00:29:26.860 --> 00:29:27.980
what do you think many students

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:30.530
say, not all but many?

00:29:30.530 --> 00:29:32.230
What are the forces on
it while it's rising?

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:37.276
Yeah, [? Adrian. ?]

00:29:37.276 --> 00:29:39.070
AUDIENCE: So of them will
say the force goes up.

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:41.990
PROFESSOR: Right, some will
say the force goes up.

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:44.078
They'll say mg up.

00:29:46.810 --> 00:29:49.110
I see people laughing, and
that's a good reaction,

00:29:49.110 --> 00:29:51.090
because that shows you're
learning something about how

00:29:51.090 --> 00:29:51.680
students think.

00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:52.620
That's kind of amazing.

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:55.410
Why would they possibly
say that?

00:29:55.410 --> 00:29:59.640
Well let's talk about this one,
and you'll see that it's

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:02.620
actually a similar mode
of reasoning to this.

00:30:02.620 --> 00:30:05.170
So what you'll find
is even students

00:30:05.170 --> 00:30:06.410
who get this correct--

00:30:06.410 --> 00:30:08.400
so this isn't right.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:10.440
It's mg down.

00:30:10.440 --> 00:30:12.940
But there's a deep seated
misconception that if

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:14.690
something's moving upwards,
it has to have a

00:30:14.690 --> 00:30:16.400
force pushing it upwards.

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:18.070
And then the force
somehow gets used

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:20.480
up, and then it stops.

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:22.040
OK, well what about here?

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:25.540
So now they'll agree that
there's weight pushing down.

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:26.790
So that's the mg.

00:30:29.790 --> 00:30:31.700
And then the question is,
what's the other force?

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:33.190
And they call it by
different names.

00:30:33.190 --> 00:30:35.900
In America, it's called the
normal force, which is a

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:37.370
terrible name.

00:30:37.370 --> 00:30:40.070
And in England it's called the
reaction force, which is a

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:41.960
terrible name for
another reason.

00:30:41.960 --> 00:30:44.780
Which is that it implies
that it's the

00:30:44.780 --> 00:30:47.570
result, somehow a reaction.

00:30:47.570 --> 00:30:49.920
So it's a terrible name.

00:30:49.920 --> 00:30:52.880
But let's ask the students,
how big is this force?

00:30:52.880 --> 00:30:53.860
OK, so it's upwards.

00:30:53.860 --> 00:30:54.950
Everyone agrees that
it's upwards.

00:30:54.950 --> 00:31:01.530
But how big, r or n, depending
on which country you're in?

00:31:01.530 --> 00:31:07.140
So take a minute or two and for
yourself figure out how

00:31:07.140 --> 00:31:12.270
big the reaction force or the
normal force is, in comparison

00:31:12.270 --> 00:31:14.200
with the weight.

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:18.330
So this is a small steel ball
dropped from say a meter and

00:31:18.330 --> 00:31:19.650
bouncing off a steel table.

00:31:22.580 --> 00:31:25.980
So two questions, first figure
out what you think.

00:31:25.980 --> 00:31:27.690
And second, figure out what
you think students

00:31:27.690 --> 00:31:29.020
are going to say.

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:32.460
OK so you're doing both,
trying to get

00:31:32.460 --> 00:31:33.710
into the student mind.

00:31:38.940 --> 00:31:41.220
Let's do a quick vote.

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:43.310
So what's the ratio between
that normal

00:31:43.310 --> 00:31:44.560
force and the weight?

00:31:47.370 --> 00:31:48.900
So who votes for equal?

00:31:48.900 --> 00:31:51.350
First we'll do what you think,
and then we'll do what

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:52.020
students think.

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:53.270
So who thinks they're equal?

00:31:57.600 --> 00:31:58.850
Two to one?

00:32:02.430 --> 00:32:06.740
Greater than 10, but
not quite 1,000?

00:32:06.740 --> 00:32:10.840
Greater than 1,000 to 1?

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:13.320
OK now what do you think
students say?

00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:15.560
How many say one to one?

00:32:19.610 --> 00:32:21.080
How many say two to one?

00:32:23.620 --> 00:32:24.870
How many say greater than 10?

00:32:27.870 --> 00:32:30.840
Greater than 1,000?

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:34.790
And how many are not sure what
the students are going to say?

00:32:34.790 --> 00:32:37.600
So actually when you ask the
students it depends on the

00:32:37.600 --> 00:32:38.230
population.

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:45.870
But generally, what I find is
it's 90% for one to one, And

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:49.320
about 10% for two to one.

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:52.130
And no one says anything else.

00:32:52.130 --> 00:32:54.790
OK so now why would students
say one to one?

00:32:57.310 --> 00:33:00.640
What's the reasoning going
on in their mind?

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:02.420
Has no velocity.

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:05.160
So that is exactly the
same reasoning as

00:33:05.160 --> 00:33:07.340
this, with mg upwards.

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:09.470
But what's interesting is even
the students who know it's mg

00:33:09.470 --> 00:33:13.830
downwards still say, well
the velocity is zero.

00:33:13.830 --> 00:33:16.130
So v equals zero.

00:33:16.130 --> 00:33:17.790
Therefore, it's in
equilibrium.

00:33:17.790 --> 00:33:19.890
Therefore, there's no
forces acting on it.

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:22.520
Therefore, the reaction force,
or the normal force, and the

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:25.800
weight have to cancel.

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:30.030
N equals mg because
it's stopped.

00:33:30.030 --> 00:33:34.920
So that what I call that is I
call that the f equals mv

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:37.550
theory of physics.

00:33:37.550 --> 00:33:39.270
Now maybe like in the linguistic
books, I'll put a

00:33:39.270 --> 00:33:42.210
star by that saying
don't say that.

00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:44.870
That's not how you translate
that sentence into real life.

00:33:44.870 --> 00:33:46.500
But why f equals mv?

00:33:46.500 --> 00:33:48.330
Why is it so deep seeded?

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:51.760
Well we have a gazillion hours
of experience with it.

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:55.930
Suppose I move a object,
and I push it.

00:33:55.930 --> 00:33:58.180
Stop pushing it, and
it stops moving.

00:33:58.180 --> 00:34:00.800
If I have a light object,
I just push it a

00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:01.880
little less and it moves.

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:03.640
And I stop pushing, and
it stops moving.

00:34:03.640 --> 00:34:08.130
So f is related to m, and f is
related to v. This seems to

00:34:08.130 --> 00:34:10.110
explain most of our world.

00:34:10.110 --> 00:34:11.360
It's hard to get around that.

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:14.310
So the question is, how do you
actually try to force the

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:17.460
students to see that that's
actually completely junk what

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:21.150
they said, and that
it can't be equal?

00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:26.500
And the way I want to do it is
I want to do it in a way that

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:29.440
recombines their intuitive model
and their school model.

00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:31.250
I want to meld them together.

00:34:31.250 --> 00:34:33.350
So the way I do that
is the following,

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:35.070
which is I get a rock.

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:36.850
So let's call this a rock.

00:34:36.850 --> 00:34:38.659
And I ask one of the
students, could I

00:34:38.659 --> 00:34:40.239
please borrow your hand?

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:41.659
And so somebody gives
me their hand.

00:34:41.659 --> 00:34:44.310
And I say, OK, I'm going to
put the rock in your hand.

00:34:44.310 --> 00:34:47.560
Now, what's the weight
of the rock?

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:47.825
mg.

00:34:47.825 --> 00:34:48.360
OK, great.

00:34:48.360 --> 00:34:50.580
So what's the force of the
rock on your hand? mg.

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:52.110
Great.

00:34:52.110 --> 00:34:56.300
Now I hold the rock about the
same place I'm going to drop

00:34:56.300 --> 00:34:58.770
the steel ball, and I say, OK
on the count of three, I'm

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:00.630
going to drop the rock
on your hand.

00:35:00.630 --> 00:35:03.080
One, two, and then I'm ready.

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:04.120
What are they going to do?

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:05.130
Like that.

00:35:05.130 --> 00:35:07.180
And soon as they try to do that,
I grab their hand and

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:08.080
say, wait a minute.

00:35:08.080 --> 00:35:10.280
Let's reason about this
with physics.

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:12.330
Why are you moving your hand?

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:17.570
You just told me that when the
thing bounces, it's still mg.

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:20.010
The reaction force and the
normal force is still mg.

00:35:20.010 --> 00:35:22.600
And you just showed me
that mg on your hand

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:23.590
didn't hurt your hand.

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:25.620
You could hold the rock on
your hand no problem.

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:27.250
So why are you moving
your hand?

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:29.680
So then we'll have a discussion,
and many of them

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:31.530
will then change
to two to one.

00:35:31.530 --> 00:35:34.420
They'll say, oh, well it's
actually two to one.

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:36.840
And I say OK, two to one, well
I have an answer for that.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:38.740
Two rocks.

00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:41.830
So I have two rocks, and I
put them on their hand.

00:35:41.830 --> 00:35:46.410
So now compared to the
first rock, mg, 2mg.

00:35:46.410 --> 00:35:47.820
So now I take the first
rock, and I'm going to

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:49.090
drop it on your hand.

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:50.530
And one, two, three.

00:35:50.530 --> 00:35:51.700
And they try to move.

00:35:51.700 --> 00:35:52.740
And I say wait, wait.

00:35:52.740 --> 00:35:54.370
You just told me 2mg was fine.

00:35:54.370 --> 00:35:56.180
This felt fine to you, right?

00:35:56.180 --> 00:35:59.780
And they say, I know it's
going to hurt like hell.

00:35:59.780 --> 00:36:04.230
So now what they're doing is
they now have some kind of

00:36:04.230 --> 00:36:06.850
contradiction that's evident
between the school model and

00:36:06.850 --> 00:36:07.890
the intuitive model.

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:13.010
And now is your opportunity to
introduce and explain, yeah

00:36:13.010 --> 00:36:14.040
you're right.

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:17.550
Your intuitive model is actually
correct in this case.

00:36:17.550 --> 00:36:20.240
And your school model reasoning
is incorrect.

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:21.810
So actually what we're going
to do is try to move the

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:24.440
school model towards a piece of
your intuitive model that

00:36:24.440 --> 00:36:25.290
is correct.

00:36:25.290 --> 00:36:27.690
We're trying to get away from
the f equals mv part of the

00:36:27.690 --> 00:36:31.690
intuitive model and emphasize
the part that does know.

00:36:31.690 --> 00:36:33.990
And the part that says, I don't
want to have that rock

00:36:33.990 --> 00:36:35.730
in my hand is correct.

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:39.600
So then they're very ready to do
a school model calculation

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:41.500
of how big the force is.

00:36:41.500 --> 00:36:44.850
And it turns out to be something
like 100,000 or

00:36:44.850 --> 00:36:47.200
10,000 times the weight.

00:36:47.200 --> 00:36:51.090
So it's huge because the impact
time is so short.

00:36:51.090 --> 00:36:54.070
And then to make that plausible
to them, we can

00:36:54.070 --> 00:36:56.770
actually calculate the impact
time or estimate it.

00:36:56.770 --> 00:36:59.530
But then you can actually say,
look you already know this.

00:36:59.530 --> 00:37:01.260
You intuitively understand
that.

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:03.742
Because if you--

00:37:03.742 --> 00:37:05.570
again I'll stand on the table.

00:37:08.990 --> 00:37:13.080
Suppose you're going to jump off
an object like this, what

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:15.050
do you do when you land?

00:37:15.050 --> 00:37:16.940
What does everyone do?

00:37:16.940 --> 00:37:17.680
Bend your knees.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:19.610
Right, so you do that.

00:37:19.610 --> 00:37:20.710
And what does that do?

00:37:20.710 --> 00:37:22.995
That increases the
contact time.

00:37:22.995 --> 00:37:25.030
And why are you increasing
the contact time?

00:37:25.030 --> 00:37:28.430
Because that decreases
the acceleration.

00:37:28.430 --> 00:37:32.000
The acceleration is a change
in velocity divided by the

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.020
contact time.

00:37:33.020 --> 00:37:36.150
So you can't affect the change
in velocity very much.

00:37:36.150 --> 00:37:38.540
That's either v or 2v or
something like that.

00:37:38.540 --> 00:37:40.340
But the content time
you can change.

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:42.020
So with the steel ball,
contact time is

00:37:42.020 --> 00:37:43.350
actually very short.

00:37:43.350 --> 00:37:45.110
Because the speed of
sound is so fast.

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:48.470
So the impact force
is really high.

00:37:48.470 --> 00:37:52.010
So yes, your intuitive
model was correct.

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:53.920
And now we're yanking the
school model towards it.

00:37:53.920 --> 00:37:56.360
So you actually bring
the two together.

00:37:56.360 --> 00:37:58.540
And you fight the divergence.

00:37:58.540 --> 00:38:02.290
So you want to look for
examples like that

00:38:02.290 --> 00:38:03.970
whenever you can.

00:38:03.970 --> 00:38:07.900
And to summarize the lesson--
because it was pointed out

00:38:07.900 --> 00:38:10.130
that I should summarize
more often--

00:38:10.130 --> 00:38:15.010
the summary of the entire theme
about misconceptions is

00:38:15.010 --> 00:38:18.380
that you need to understand
that so that

00:38:18.380 --> 00:38:19.360
you can teach properly.

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:22.930
Because there's no way to deduce
this without doing

00:38:22.930 --> 00:38:24.620
that, which we're going
to talk about later.

00:38:24.620 --> 00:38:27.350
But even knowing that, if you
don't know this, you can't run

00:38:27.350 --> 00:38:29.840
the system backwards and figure
out what goes here.

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:34.410
And so then, how do you actually
learn about this?

00:38:34.410 --> 00:38:35.960
Well you've done one way.

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:37.450
You've done one way already.

00:38:37.450 --> 00:38:41.370
Let me write down two or
three ways for you.

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:52.810
So the question is, how
to learn about s,

00:38:52.810 --> 00:38:53.920
the students' system.

00:38:53.920 --> 00:38:55.270
Well one way is to read.

00:38:58.930 --> 00:39:01.990
So in many fields, there's lots
of research about what

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:04.760
particular misconceptions
students have.

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:08.430
And I've given you some of those
readings on the website.

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:10.450
But there's a whole vast
body of literature, and

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:11.650
many fields have that.

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:13.270
So you can look at that.

00:39:13.270 --> 00:39:15.920
Another way, and this is--

00:39:21.970 --> 00:39:24.540
so this is shut your mouth.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:25.540
Now why is that?

00:39:25.540 --> 00:39:28.090
Well there's no way to really
understand what students are

00:39:28.090 --> 00:39:30.030
thinking unless you ask them.

00:39:30.030 --> 00:39:33.310
And if you don't let them talk,
you're not going to

00:39:33.310 --> 00:39:35.690
actually hear what
they're thinking.

00:39:35.690 --> 00:39:37.330
You'll actually put words
into their mouth.

00:39:37.330 --> 00:39:40.290
Because you won't imagine that
they think f equals mv.

00:39:40.290 --> 00:39:41.720
You never would imagine that.

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:43.790
So you have to shut your
mouth and listen.

00:39:46.430 --> 00:39:50.860
So office hours is a
chance for that.

00:39:50.860 --> 00:39:53.560
And related to that is
the feedback sheet.

00:39:58.790 --> 00:40:01.660
If students get in the habit of
asking you questions about

00:40:01.660 --> 00:40:04.080
what was confusing, you start
to build a model of the

00:40:04.080 --> 00:40:06.765
students' system, what worked
and what didn't work and what

00:40:06.765 --> 00:40:07.850
was confusing for them.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:12.640
So all of these ways are ways to
build models of s, which is

00:40:12.640 --> 00:40:17.720
absolutely necessary
for deducing t.

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:18.970
Any questions?

00:40:24.300 --> 00:40:27.070
OK so if you could
do two things.

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:29.070
One is to spend one
minute filling out

00:40:29.070 --> 00:40:31.190
the feedback sheet.

00:40:31.190 --> 00:40:37.080
And the other is everyone who
has a homework equation

00:40:37.080 --> 00:40:40.010
treatment, please
raise your hand.

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:40.810
OK that's great.

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:45.070
So now just find one person
near you to swap with.

00:40:45.070 --> 00:40:46.160
Question?

00:40:46.160 --> 00:40:46.610
Yeah, OK.

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:47.100
So that's great.

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:50.620
So just find one person who has
one near you to swap with

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:52.300
and give each other comments.

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:57.690
And then just write your name
over the next week and bring

00:40:57.690 --> 00:41:00.590
it in next time with you.

00:41:00.590 --> 00:41:02.690
So basically this is a way--

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:04.810
and if there's no one near
you, or they've already

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:06.370
swapped, just make
a group of three.

00:41:06.370 --> 00:41:09.360
It's no big deal.

00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:11.190
Does anyone not have someone
to swap with?

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:14.670
OK great.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:17.030
And so introduce yourself
to the other person.

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:18.980
It doesn't matter if you're
in different fields.

00:41:18.980 --> 00:41:21.900
It often can be an advantage,
because you'll get a fresh set

00:41:21.900 --> 00:41:24.360
of eyes on it.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:26.990
And I'll give you some
directions by email about what

00:41:26.990 --> 00:41:28.620
to look for and put
it on the website.

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:31.150
But generally just give each
other suggestions and work

00:41:31.150 --> 00:41:33.690
together on what you
thought was a good

00:41:33.690 --> 00:41:34.350
and what wasn't good.

00:41:34.350 --> 00:41:37.300
And just write your name on the
person you commented on.

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:38.870
And then you'll bring
them both in.

00:41:38.870 --> 00:41:42.800
You'll bring the commented sheet
from the other person in

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:44.610
the next time.

00:41:44.610 --> 00:41:46.470
Or you'll just give it back
to them and bring it.

00:41:46.470 --> 00:41:48.110
This is not a big
police exercise.

00:41:48.110 --> 00:41:51.150
I just want you to meet
somebody else and have

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:52.630
practice discussing
these things and

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:54.770
learn from each other.

00:41:54.770 --> 00:41:56.470
So questions about that?

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:04.540
So if you could finish filling
out the sheets and bring the

00:42:04.540 --> 00:42:07.970
sheets either here or
here, I'll pack up.

00:42:07.970 --> 00:42:11.120
And meanwhile we'll have any
questions that people want to

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:14.830
talk to me about individually
outside, because I think

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:17.350
there's another class that 's
going to come streaming in

00:42:17.350 --> 00:42:20.490
with like 150 people.

00:42:20.490 --> 00:42:24.050
So remember, learn about
the student system.

00:42:24.050 --> 00:42:27.480
It's probably the most important
thing to do to make

00:42:27.480 --> 00:42:29.220
your teaching stand
out and have long

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:30.470
lasting, good effects.

