PROFESSOR: So first, questions
from before.

00:42:43.660 --> 00:42:44.870
One of the comments--

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:48.970
well, let's see, two of them
were that could we have less

00:42:48.970 --> 00:42:52.380
time for questions, but also
they're very helpful.

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:53.730
So there's always
a tension there.

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:57.740
So what I'm going to try to do
is shorten some of the total

00:42:57.740 --> 00:43:01.080
answers to the questions and
then maybe put some answers to

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:06.050
the questions towards the end
of the lecture as well.

00:43:06.050 --> 00:43:09.230
I do like to try to answer
most of the questions.

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:12.720
And the reason being is that
it provides also pacing.

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:14.090
And you'll find that too.

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:17.180
If you find yourself generating
four times as many

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:20.150
questions as you have time to
answer the next time, it

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:23.160
probably means you did way too
much stuff the previous time.

00:43:23.160 --> 00:43:26.980
So it gives you feedback signal
on how much material to

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:29.080
discuss in the class time.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:35.690
And so that's one reason I'm
reluctant to just put all the

00:43:35.690 --> 00:43:36.970
answers on the web.

00:43:36.970 --> 00:43:40.620
Because that's sort of like
teaching with slides where you

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:43.270
can just flip through all the
equations really fast, and it

00:43:43.270 --> 00:43:45.070
seems like you got through
a lot of equations.

00:43:45.070 --> 00:43:47.680
But actually no one really
understood the equations.

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:50.240
So it's sort of a symptomatic
treatment for a more

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:52.500
fundamental problem which may
be that I'm doing too many

00:43:52.500 --> 00:43:55.490
things and not allowing enough
time for questions in the

00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:56.740
class itself.

00:43:59.330 --> 00:44:01.120
A general question, which
is, how do you

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:02.750
evaluate your own teaching?

00:44:02.750 --> 00:44:06.270
When you feel good or bad about
how class just went?

00:44:06.270 --> 00:44:09.090
And what metrics do I use
popularity, covering what I

00:44:09.090 --> 00:44:10.650
set out to?

00:44:10.650 --> 00:44:11.770
How do I know?

00:44:11.770 --> 00:44:14.610
So one major way
is I use these.

00:44:17.430 --> 00:44:20.690
It's not really that I say, oh
did people hate it or like it?

00:44:20.690 --> 00:44:22.700
I mean, I want to know if people
hated it or liked it.

00:44:22.700 --> 00:44:25.680
And I just I don't just add up
the likes and the hates and

00:44:25.680 --> 00:44:28.690
say OK, 10 likes minus
3 hates equals 7.

00:44:28.690 --> 00:44:30.290
That's great.

00:44:30.290 --> 00:44:34.200
You're batting 80%.

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:37.940
But I try to get a sense from
reading the comments of what

00:44:37.940 --> 00:44:40.570
people were confused about,
what was interesting to

00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:45.330
people, and sort of integrate
that up and imagine the whole

00:44:45.330 --> 00:44:47.860
class as one giant
student mind.

00:44:47.860 --> 00:44:51.660
And I want to know how I connect
the material to the

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:53.300
collective student mind.

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:57.040
So I evaluate it that way, sort
of intuitively from the

00:44:57.040 --> 00:44:58.960
comments that people
make on the sheet.

00:44:58.960 --> 00:45:01.240
Which is why I hand out the
sheet every time, and I think

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:02.490
the sheet is so valuable.

00:45:05.180 --> 00:45:10.110
Now another way, covering the
materials I set out to.

00:45:10.110 --> 00:45:13.320
Well I'm probably sort of on one
extreme of that, which I

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:16.240
don't really care how much
material I covered.

00:45:16.240 --> 00:45:19.030
But let me explain why
I'm on that extreme.

00:45:19.030 --> 00:45:22.370
So some people only care about
how much material is covered.

00:45:22.370 --> 00:45:25.550
And some people are
more on my end.

00:45:25.550 --> 00:45:26.925
So I'll give you the reason.

00:45:26.925 --> 00:45:28.810
And most people I would
say on this edge.

00:45:28.810 --> 00:45:30.640
So I don't need to really
justify that, because you've

00:45:30.640 --> 00:45:32.220
heard lots of reasons
for that.

00:45:32.220 --> 00:45:37.080
But it's the other side,
why do I not care?

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:41.580
Well I don't care so much just
because I think class time and

00:45:41.580 --> 00:45:46.310
a lecture course is such a small
part of a student's life

00:45:46.310 --> 00:45:49.860
that if you haven't connected
to the students, if you

00:45:49.860 --> 00:45:52.450
haven't made it click for them
and got them interested, made

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:55.460
them want to continue studying,
then you've lost

00:45:55.460 --> 00:45:57.210
most of the effect
of the teaching.

00:45:57.210 --> 00:45:59.760
The effect of the teaching isn't
really going to be so

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:01.000
much in the class.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.450
Because what you can do is you
can kindle interest, kindle a

00:46:04.450 --> 00:46:06.040
way of looking at the world.

00:46:06.040 --> 00:46:08.360
But it's really up to the
students to carry that on

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:09.060
afterwards.

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.600
And if you've actually bored
them, or they've decided that

00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:14.860
this whole material is
useless, they're

00:46:14.860 --> 00:46:15.930
not going to do that.

00:46:15.930 --> 00:46:18.090
And then it's all just going
to go away anyway.

00:46:18.090 --> 00:46:20.840
So actually what I'm much more
interested in is how much I've

00:46:20.840 --> 00:46:21.830
kindled those interests.

00:46:21.830 --> 00:46:25.610
And that's what I try to
judge using the sheets.

00:46:25.610 --> 00:46:28.430
And I think that's actually what
produces the long term

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:29.680
change in ways of thinking.

00:46:32.310 --> 00:46:37.360
Another comment was that the
rock experiment rocked, which

00:46:37.360 --> 00:46:39.960
I thought was a good pun.

00:46:39.960 --> 00:46:43.190
If you're not willing to write
out detailed derivations on

00:46:43.190 --> 00:46:46.010
the board, is it more important
to have more detail

00:46:46.010 --> 00:46:48.070
published lecture notes?

00:46:48.070 --> 00:46:49.660
And yeah I think that's right.

00:46:49.660 --> 00:46:52.360
In fact, that's generally
necessary.

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:54.390
But it doesn't have to be your
own published notes.

00:46:54.390 --> 00:46:56.850
It could just be a book
you refer people to.

00:46:56.850 --> 00:47:01.790
So we've sort of gone backwards
from Gutenberg.

00:47:01.790 --> 00:47:05.630
In the days before Gutenberg,
everyone read out their notes.

00:47:05.630 --> 00:47:07.250
That was what monasteries did.

00:47:07.250 --> 00:47:08.650
You read out the bible.

00:47:08.650 --> 00:47:11.420
And at the end of a year or two
of doing that, you had 50

00:47:11.420 --> 00:47:13.850
bibles, because everyone took
notes on what you read.

00:47:13.850 --> 00:47:19.410
That was the old photocopier,
back in say the year 1300.

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:23.160
And then when Gutenberg came
along the universities then

00:47:23.160 --> 00:47:24.280
did the same thing.

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:25.440
That's what universities were.

00:47:25.440 --> 00:47:26.840
They basically grew out
of the monasteries.

00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:31.050
Then Gutenberg came along and
said, oh actually books are

00:47:31.050 --> 00:47:33.340
cheap now, well much cheaper
than before.

00:47:33.340 --> 00:47:36.570
Books used to cost roughly
say $5,000 a

00:47:36.570 --> 00:47:38.540
book in today's dollars.

00:47:38.540 --> 00:47:41.750
But then with Gutenberg and
automatic printing, they could

00:47:41.750 --> 00:47:42.670
be much cheaper.

00:47:42.670 --> 00:47:45.430
So you can-- and we've developed
printing technology

00:47:45.430 --> 00:47:46.410
much farther.

00:47:46.410 --> 00:47:50.160
So actually for a while until
word processing came along and

00:47:50.160 --> 00:47:53.090
typesetting on your computer,
people would actually just

00:47:53.090 --> 00:47:55.190
refer people to books and say,
OK you're a student.

00:47:55.190 --> 00:47:57.090
You are expected to
read these books.

00:47:57.090 --> 00:47:59.615
But now that people can make
their own notes, people have

00:47:59.615 --> 00:48:03.330
sort of forgot how to tell
people to use books.

00:48:03.330 --> 00:48:07.750
And instead people, the
lecturers, just tend to write

00:48:07.750 --> 00:48:08.910
their own notes out.

00:48:08.910 --> 00:48:12.240
And the students actually seem
for some crazy reason to

00:48:12.240 --> 00:48:16.760
basically except notes
specifically for that topic

00:48:16.760 --> 00:48:19.230
and don't want to read books.

00:48:19.230 --> 00:48:21.470
So it gets really strange.

00:48:21.470 --> 00:48:23.870
You get in these bizarre cycles
where you make notes.

00:48:23.870 --> 00:48:26.700
And as long as you have notes
that seem like they're key to

00:48:26.700 --> 00:48:28.310
the lecture, that's great.

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:29.370
Students will read them.

00:48:29.370 --> 00:48:31.430
And then you assemble all the
notes for the very same

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:33.540
lectures into a book,
and now suppose

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:35.180
the book gets published.

00:48:35.180 --> 00:48:37.870
The students will say, well
now we want notes again.

00:48:37.870 --> 00:48:41.560
You can't say, well there's the
book which was the notes.

00:48:41.560 --> 00:48:44.170
Because it's not specifically
targeted.

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:46.890
So part of the cure for
that is reading memos.

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:49.890
Or any way of teaching students
to do reading is to

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:52.870
shift back to taking advantage
of Gutenberg.

00:48:52.870 --> 00:48:54.650
And then once we take advantage
of Gutenberg, we can

00:48:54.650 --> 00:48:57.880
worry about taking advantage of
all the web technology and

00:48:57.880 --> 00:48:59.980
word processing technology
that we have.

00:48:59.980 --> 00:49:02.710
But yeah, it is important, to
answer the question directly,

00:49:02.710 --> 00:49:06.210
to have the details somewhere
for the students.

00:49:06.210 --> 00:49:08.620
And the best place generally
is in printed material,

00:49:08.620 --> 00:49:12.160
whether in a book or in
something you write.

00:49:12.160 --> 00:49:16.160
Because writing it on the
board is very noisy.

00:49:16.160 --> 00:49:19.850
By which I mean that it's
very easy to mis-copy.

00:49:19.850 --> 00:49:22.030
It's easy for you to
make mistakes.

00:49:22.030 --> 00:49:23.850
It's easier for the student to
make mistakes when they're

00:49:23.850 --> 00:49:24.940
taking notes.

00:49:24.940 --> 00:49:29.830
It's best to have it all in
print, and also it's best to

00:49:29.830 --> 00:49:32.790
put the high level stuff in
lecture, and have all the

00:49:32.790 --> 00:49:38.410
details with the students in
their own comfortable space

00:49:38.410 --> 00:49:41.780
when they have time to
go back and forth.

00:49:41.780 --> 00:49:46.370
OK, so then there were several
questions about how do you

00:49:46.370 --> 00:49:50.010
meld the intuitive model
and the school model?

00:49:50.010 --> 00:49:51.080
Are their general principles?

00:49:51.080 --> 00:49:54.850
So I talked about how for
example with the rock example

00:49:54.850 --> 00:50:00.670
that the school model is that
when the rock isn't moving,

00:50:00.670 --> 00:50:03.190
the force is zero because
it's in equilibrium.

00:50:03.190 --> 00:50:05.060
So the net force is zero.

00:50:05.060 --> 00:50:08.640
So the reaction force
equals the weight.

00:50:08.640 --> 00:50:10.000
So that's the school model.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:14.270
The intuitive model, somewhere
in there is an intuitive model

00:50:14.270 --> 00:50:16.850
that you don't want the rock
to fall on your hand.

00:50:16.850 --> 00:50:19.080
So what's a general
ideas behind

00:50:19.080 --> 00:50:20.060
melding those two models?

00:50:20.060 --> 00:50:23.690
So that demonstration I showed
of borrowing someone's hand

00:50:23.690 --> 00:50:25.850
and dropping a rock on it, well
not quite dropping the

00:50:25.850 --> 00:50:28.210
rock on it, but threatening
to, Is one way.

00:50:28.210 --> 00:50:31.020
But what are the general
principles behind that?

00:50:31.020 --> 00:50:35.710
So the general principles are
that you want to connect to

00:50:35.710 --> 00:50:38.530
where all the mental
hardware is.

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:43.196
So generally symbolic processing
it's a sort of

00:50:43.196 --> 00:50:45.460
surface phenomenon
in the brain.

00:50:45.460 --> 00:50:47.900
It's linguistic.

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:52.280
It's only about 100,000 years
old, whereas perceptual

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:56.850
reasoning, visual reasoning,
visceral reasoning, those are

00:50:56.850 --> 00:50:58.650
hundreds of millions
of years old.

00:50:58.650 --> 00:51:01.790
Organisms have been seeing
things for hundreds of

00:51:01.790 --> 00:51:03.010
millions of years.

00:51:03.010 --> 00:51:05.540
So there's a huge difference
in the amount of

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:06.790
hardware that we have.

00:51:14.790 --> 00:51:17.120
So symbolic hardware
say has evolved for

00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:19.620
10 to the five years.

00:51:19.620 --> 00:51:29.880
And perceptual, rough estimates
10 to the five

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:30.710
versus 10 to eight years.

00:51:30.710 --> 00:51:34.640
So there's about 1,000 times
more evolutionary help for

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:35.620
these things.

00:51:35.620 --> 00:51:37.750
So if you want to meld--

00:51:37.750 --> 00:51:41.040
and this is basically where
the intuitive model, the

00:51:41.040 --> 00:51:42.560
internal model lives.

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:46.170
So if you want to change it, you
have to connect to where

00:51:46.170 --> 00:51:46.890
the model lives.

00:51:46.890 --> 00:51:49.000
You have to do things
that are perceptual.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:53.270
So visual arguments, visceral
arguments, auditory

00:51:53.270 --> 00:51:56.930
demonstrations, things
they create conflict.

00:51:56.930 --> 00:51:59.440
Somehow some kind of conflict
is also another general

00:51:59.440 --> 00:52:03.350
principle, where you expose
some kind of obvious

00:52:03.350 --> 00:52:04.650
contradiction.

00:52:04.650 --> 00:52:08.190
And that's so beneficial,
because that's self teaching.

00:52:08.190 --> 00:52:10.820
As long as there's a
contradiction, the students

00:52:10.820 --> 00:52:13.250
know that the problem
isn't done.

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:16.290
So in the rock example, there's
a contradiction

00:52:16.290 --> 00:52:19.740
between, I don't want the
rock dropping on my

00:52:19.740 --> 00:52:22.310
hand on the one hand--

00:52:22.310 --> 00:52:24.100
that's the perceptual view--

00:52:24.100 --> 00:52:28.760
with the symbolic one, which
is net force is zero so the

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:31.130
reaction force equals mg.

00:52:31.130 --> 00:52:32.630
So there's a contradiction.

00:52:32.630 --> 00:52:34.880
As long as you can't get the
same answer by two different

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:36.830
ways, you know you still
have more to learn.

00:52:36.830 --> 00:52:37.800
So it's self-teaching.

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:38.940
You don't have to wait
for the teacher to

00:52:38.940 --> 00:52:40.240
say, oh wait a minute.

00:52:40.240 --> 00:52:41.150
That's not the right answer.

00:52:41.150 --> 00:52:42.720
You know on your own.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:43.620
So know on your own.

00:52:43.620 --> 00:52:45.670
You internally feel that there's
something wrong.

00:52:45.670 --> 00:52:48.340
So you're tapping
in, I would say

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:50.160
contradictions and puzzles.

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:52.570
They're somewhat symbolic, but
they're also kind of visceral.

00:52:52.570 --> 00:52:54.940
You feel them like oh, my
god that can't be right.

00:52:54.940 --> 00:52:57.740
So if you can tap into that as
well that's another way of

00:52:57.740 --> 00:52:58.990
trying to meld the models.

00:53:03.130 --> 00:53:03.710
It's interesting.

00:53:03.710 --> 00:53:06.280
I think it's a fundamentally
important point about teaching

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:07.340
these two models.

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:11.090
And I've never seen it
discussed anywhere.

00:53:11.090 --> 00:53:14.040
So you're the sort of first
people to hear it officially

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:15.970
as far as I can tell.

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:18.980
So any questions actually
about that model?

00:53:18.980 --> 00:53:20.330
Because I think it
