00:55:29.077 --> 00:55:31.025
AUDIENCE: See, that's
encouragement to build up

00:55:31.025 --> 00:55:32.000
[INAUDIBLE]

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:33.920
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so you want
to encourage that.

00:55:33.920 --> 00:55:35.680
And it's true--

00:55:35.680 --> 00:55:35.950
pardon?

00:55:35.950 --> 00:55:37.780
AUDIENCE: It's not built in?

00:55:37.780 --> 00:55:41.040
PROFESSOR: I would say that the
field itself pushes things

00:55:41.040 --> 00:55:41.970
towards symbolic.

00:55:41.970 --> 00:55:44.570
Just because it is a symbol
manipulation device.

00:55:44.570 --> 00:55:47.650
So that's what makes computers
so much better at what they do

00:55:47.650 --> 00:55:48.430
compared to humans.

00:55:48.430 --> 00:55:49.890
That's why we use computers.

00:55:49.890 --> 00:55:52.860
Because we're so bad at symbol
manipulation, and computers

00:55:52.860 --> 00:55:54.360
are so good at it.

00:55:54.360 --> 00:55:56.430
So our ways of solving problems
are going to be very

00:55:56.430 --> 00:55:57.950
different than computers.

00:55:57.950 --> 00:56:01.890
But the problem that we have
when we're using computers, we

00:56:01.890 --> 00:56:03.990
have to solve with
human hardware.

00:56:03.990 --> 00:56:06.510
So when the computer isn't doing
what we want, we have to

00:56:06.510 --> 00:56:10.160
try to find some way of
understanding what's going on.

00:56:10.160 --> 00:56:13.170
And it can't be just purely
symbolic, because

00:56:13.170 --> 00:56:14.420
we're bad at that.

00:56:14.420 --> 00:56:16.070
So you can't--

00:56:16.070 --> 00:56:18.390
I mean in desperation sometimes
you'll trace through

00:56:18.390 --> 00:56:21.150
every step of a program and
see what went wrong.

00:56:21.150 --> 00:56:22.600
But generally that just
overflows you

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:23.330
with tons of data.

00:56:23.330 --> 00:56:26.030
It's much better to actually try
to take a step back, break

00:56:26.030 --> 00:56:30.130
the program into parts, see big
chunks, and make sure the

00:56:30.130 --> 00:56:31.780
big chunks work.

00:56:31.780 --> 00:56:36.060
And experts do that, not sort
of automatically because

00:56:36.060 --> 00:56:37.570
they've been trained
as experts.

00:56:37.570 --> 00:56:42.670
So in any field the experts
see differently than the

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:45.760
novices, because their
perception is different.

00:56:45.760 --> 00:56:48.750
So yeah, when you're teaching
computer science to students,

00:56:48.750 --> 00:56:51.230
you want to teach them ways
that are perceptual.

00:56:51.230 --> 00:56:53.840
You want to teach them
visceral feelings.

00:56:53.840 --> 00:56:56.420
So one way to do that for
example is running time of

00:56:56.420 --> 00:56:59.200
algorithms.

00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:01.710
Different sorting algorithms
take different times.

00:57:01.710 --> 00:57:04.855
So suppose you have-- for all
the non CS people, a huge area

00:57:04.855 --> 00:57:06.320
of study in CS is sorting.

00:57:06.320 --> 00:57:08.810
Suppose you have a giant list
of numbers or list of words

00:57:08.810 --> 00:57:11.370
you want to alphabetize.

00:57:11.370 --> 00:57:12.630
Text indexing uses it.

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:14.240
All kinds of stuff
using sorting.

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:15.670
So how fast can you sort?

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:19.070
Well the naive sort of simplest
thing to program is

00:57:19.070 --> 00:57:20.320
called bubble sort.

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:29.090
And if you have n numbers, it
takes something times n

00:57:29.090 --> 00:57:31.840
squared, so flip operations.

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:34.310
So time is of order n squared.

00:57:34.310 --> 00:57:44.620
But then there's merge sort,
which is a divide and conquer

00:57:44.620 --> 00:57:46.620
algorithm, which
takes n log n.

00:57:46.620 --> 00:57:48.760
Now you could just say that.

00:57:48.760 --> 00:57:51.010
But it's also very helpful for
students to have a feel,

00:57:51.010 --> 00:57:52.840
because generally students don't
have an understanding of

00:57:52.840 --> 00:57:54.400
functions is what I found.

00:57:54.400 --> 00:57:55.960
They don't have a good
feel for what

00:57:55.960 --> 00:57:58.030
functions do and mean.

00:57:58.030 --> 00:58:00.040
So what's the difference between
n squared and n log n?

00:58:00.040 --> 00:58:02.510
Well one way is to actually
program a sort algorithm and

00:58:02.510 --> 00:58:03.760
then try it.

00:58:06.350 --> 00:58:10.010
Try both algorithms and make
your list bigger and bigger.

00:58:10.010 --> 00:58:14.430
When do you get fed up waiting
for the damn thing to finish?

00:58:14.430 --> 00:58:15.940
So that's a visceral feeling.

00:58:15.940 --> 00:58:18.730
And actually that will tell
you that there's a huge

00:58:18.730 --> 00:58:21.200
difference between n log
n and n squared.

00:58:21.200 --> 00:58:24.650
Because this guy, basically when
n is around thousand--

00:58:24.650 --> 00:58:27.430
well, actually now computers are
much faster, let's let's

00:58:27.430 --> 00:58:28.800
say 10,000--

00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:30.300
you're pretty much going
to be fed up with that.

00:58:30.300 --> 00:58:32.220
Because that's 100 million
sort operations.

00:58:32.220 --> 00:58:37.200
It's going to take five or 10
seconds, maybe even bit longer

00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:39.410
if it's written in a higher
level language.

00:58:39.410 --> 00:58:46.980
So maybe you're fed up around
n equals 10,000.

00:58:46.980 --> 00:58:49.660
Here 10,000 times log n.

00:58:49.660 --> 00:58:52.850
Well, the log of anything is
never bigger than 10, as a

00:58:52.850 --> 00:58:57.520
rough rule of thumb The reason
being that if the log of the

00:58:57.520 --> 00:59:01.130
thing were bigger than 10, then
n itself will be so big

00:59:01.130 --> 00:59:03.020
your computer couldn't
even fit it.

00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:04.970
So you're not even dealing with
numbers whose logs are

00:59:04.970 --> 00:59:05.370
bigger than 10.

00:59:05.370 --> 00:59:08.400
It depends on the base, but
roughly speaking in base 10

00:59:08.400 --> 00:59:10.260
logarithm, it's never going
to be bigger than 10.

00:59:10.260 --> 00:59:12.420
So this is say at most 10.

00:59:12.420 --> 00:59:15.640
And so if you have a 10,000
only times a 10 here.

00:59:15.640 --> 00:59:17.790
Whereas here you have
10,000 times 10,000.

00:59:17.790 --> 00:59:23.340
Here you can go up easily to a
million before you get fed up.

00:59:25.880 --> 00:59:29.150
So the fed up is a connection
to a visceral reasoning.

00:59:29.150 --> 00:59:31.860
And actually it then makes the
difference between these

00:59:31.860 --> 00:59:32.720
really, really apparent.

00:59:32.720 --> 00:59:35.240
So there's ways you can
do it even there.

00:59:35.240 --> 00:59:36.572
Question?

00:59:36.572 --> 00:59:43.610
AUDIENCE: I think that in the
science fields that, if you

00:59:43.610 --> 00:59:46.875
really understood what you're
teaching, then you should be

00:59:46.875 --> 00:59:49.350
able to basically put it
into a simplification.

00:59:49.350 --> 00:59:51.740
Because then it's basically
summarizing everything, and

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:55.308
it's just so much better
and closer.

00:59:55.308 --> 00:59:58.194
I mean, if you write for example
a term paper or a

00:59:58.194 --> 01:00:03.210
proposal or whatever, you can
write a one page text

01:00:03.210 --> 01:00:05.489
basically, or you can make a
figure or a nice sketch.

01:00:05.489 --> 01:00:08.660
It's the same information.

01:00:08.660 --> 01:00:11.260
PROFESSOR: Right so the comment
was that if you really

01:00:11.260 --> 01:00:14.550
understand something, you can
make a really compact

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:15.790
pictorial representation.

01:00:15.790 --> 01:00:16.950
That's generally true.

01:00:16.950 --> 01:00:21.010
And that's why it takes really
long time to make those.

01:00:21.010 --> 01:00:24.750
So when you're making talks,
for example, when we talk

01:00:24.750 --> 01:00:28.000
about this later in the term,
when you're making talks and

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:31.870
slides, a really good model
for making slides is--

01:00:31.870 --> 01:00:33.120
here's a slide.

01:00:35.210 --> 01:00:37.620
This is the four to three
ratio sort of.

01:00:37.620 --> 01:00:39.090
So here is a sentence.

01:00:41.880 --> 01:00:44.060
So this is some assertion,
some message

01:00:44.060 --> 01:00:45.310
you want to get across.

01:00:48.690 --> 01:00:49.940
And here is the evidence.

01:00:52.810 --> 01:00:54.560
The body of the slide
is the evidence.

01:00:54.560 --> 01:00:57.430
And that's a picture.

01:00:57.430 --> 01:01:00.600
The best is to have some kind
of visual evidence.

01:01:00.600 --> 01:01:03.340
But what you find when you do
this-- and it is, I think, the

01:01:03.340 --> 01:01:04.600
best way to make slides--

01:01:04.600 --> 01:01:09.220
it takes a long time to really
find the best picture.

01:01:09.220 --> 01:01:11.360
And even to find a good picture
because it's just so

01:01:11.360 --> 01:01:13.110
tempting to write a bunch
of words out.

01:01:13.110 --> 01:01:15.000
But actually if you look for
that picture and you really

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:18.530
try to capture the main idea in
a picture, you will be much

01:01:18.530 --> 01:01:20.500
more successful at conveying
the messages

01:01:20.500 --> 01:01:22.280
that you want to convey.

01:01:22.280 --> 01:01:28.200
So in general, try to talk
to the perceptual system.

01:01:28.200 --> 01:01:32.730
Now there was a question related
to that which is that

01:01:32.730 --> 01:01:37.470
maybe I'm too harsh or too
negative about the symbolic

01:01:37.470 --> 01:01:38.950
ways of doing things.

01:01:38.950 --> 01:01:43.270
And the particular example was
so if you remember last time,

01:01:43.270 --> 01:01:44.855
I gave this example.

01:01:57.740 --> 01:02:00.050
So this is a pendulum, and this
is the extreme of the

01:02:00.050 --> 01:02:01.270
pendulum motion.

01:02:01.270 --> 01:02:04.955
And the question was what is
the acceleration vector at

01:02:04.955 --> 01:02:08.950
these various points
in motion.

01:02:08.950 --> 01:02:13.090
And I said, well the way to do
it is to reason intuitively

01:02:13.090 --> 01:02:15.100
about it, to figure out what
it is here and here,

01:02:15.100 --> 01:02:17.590
understand what acceleration
is, and do this one by

01:02:17.590 --> 01:02:19.780
interpolation.

01:02:19.780 --> 01:02:23.610
And the comment was well, even
if you can't do that, you can

01:02:23.610 --> 01:02:26.950
still use the Lagrangian.

01:02:26.950 --> 01:02:29.130
If I know the Lagrangian for
the system, which for the

01:02:29.130 --> 01:02:32.420
non-physicist is sort
of the elephant gun.

01:02:32.420 --> 01:02:35.990
You can solve pretty much
anything with the Lagrangian.

01:02:35.990 --> 01:02:38.280
So you can solve it with the
Lagrangian and work out the

01:02:38.280 --> 01:02:39.440
forces everywhere.

01:02:39.440 --> 01:02:40.810
And that's true.

01:02:40.810 --> 01:02:44.510
But I still maintain that
it's better to have--

01:02:44.510 --> 01:02:46.730
I'm not saying it's bad to have
a Lagrangian analysis.

01:02:46.730 --> 01:02:48.590
The more ways of doing
things is better.

01:02:48.590 --> 01:02:51.350
But there's a fundamentally
important reason why it's

01:02:51.350 --> 01:02:54.460
important to have the intuitive
way of doing it.

01:02:54.460 --> 01:02:57.830
And that is a search argument.

01:02:57.830 --> 01:03:00.130
So if you remember
from before, we

01:03:00.130 --> 01:03:03.530
talked about chunking.

01:03:03.530 --> 01:03:05.770
The experts have big
chunks, and the

01:03:05.770 --> 01:03:07.740
novices have small chunks.

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:12.220
Well we looked at the effect of
that of perception, which

01:03:12.220 --> 01:03:16.400
is that one of the proxies for
it was the chess masters could

01:03:16.400 --> 01:03:18.710
remember whole positions, and
the novices couldn't.

01:03:18.710 --> 01:03:21.600
Because their chunks were too
small, and if you remember

01:03:21.600 --> 01:03:24.130
only seven chunks, which is
typical, you can't remember a

01:03:24.130 --> 01:03:25.030
whole position.

01:03:25.030 --> 01:03:27.150
Whereas the chess master's
chunks are like three, four,

01:03:27.150 --> 01:03:27.830
five pieces.

01:03:27.830 --> 01:03:28.850
And they can easily fit a whole

01:03:28.850 --> 01:03:30.390
position in seven chunks.

01:03:30.390 --> 01:03:33.000
Well there's another, perhaps
even more fundamental

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:37.360
consequence of the different
chunk size, and that is the

01:03:37.360 --> 01:03:41.090
exponential explosion
in search space.

01:03:41.090 --> 01:03:46.290
So suppose you're here.

01:03:46.290 --> 01:03:50.160
This is your state now, and
you're looking for a solution

01:03:50.160 --> 01:03:51.510
to the problem.

01:03:51.510 --> 01:03:53.420
So suppose the solution
is here.

01:03:56.830 --> 01:03:58.155
But you don't know that yet.

01:03:58.155 --> 01:03:59.690
You're looking for
the solution.

01:03:59.690 --> 01:04:02.490
Now if your chunk size
is really big--

01:04:02.490 --> 01:04:04.540
well let's say suppose your
chunk size is really big--

01:04:04.540 --> 01:04:07.460
you'll try a few possible
chunks.

01:04:07.460 --> 01:04:10.570
OK, do any of those
get me closer?

01:04:10.570 --> 01:04:11.890
Well this one looks
a bit likely.

01:04:11.890 --> 01:04:15.600
Let me try expanding that
one, maybe that one.

01:04:15.600 --> 01:04:17.550
Try this one.

01:04:17.550 --> 01:04:19.760
And then eventually you get
your way over here.

01:04:19.760 --> 01:04:25.360
So here suppose there's four
possible approaches you could

01:04:25.360 --> 01:04:28.710
try, and because the
chunks are big,

01:04:28.710 --> 01:04:30.470
there's only three levels.

01:04:30.470 --> 01:04:36.620
So this gives you four to the
three items to search.

01:04:36.620 --> 01:04:39.670
OK, now suppose you make your
chunks really, really small.

01:04:39.670 --> 01:04:45.060
Suppose your chunks are
only half the size.

01:04:45.060 --> 01:04:49.820
So you now at every half branch
you have to search for

01:04:49.820 --> 01:04:51.310
possibilities.

01:04:51.310 --> 01:04:52.820
So this is the large chunk.

01:05:07.610 --> 01:05:11.070
So here we had one,
two, three levels.

01:05:11.070 --> 01:05:17.100
Here we're going to have six
levels, in other words, four

01:05:17.100 --> 01:05:20.410
to the six possibilities
to search.

01:05:20.410 --> 01:05:23.490
So the difference doesn't show
up in simple problems.

01:05:23.490 --> 01:05:26.670
Because you may have only one
level to go through versus two

01:05:26.670 --> 01:05:28.650
levels to go through, and
either method works.

01:05:28.650 --> 01:05:30.210
But when you're trying to
solve interesting new

01:05:30.210 --> 01:05:33.890
problems, you want your chunks
to be as large as possible so

01:05:33.890 --> 01:05:37.860
your search space collapses
to something manageable.

01:05:37.860 --> 01:05:43.870
So you don't want to have to
reason with the Lagrangian as

01:05:43.870 --> 01:05:45.500
the default mode.

01:05:45.500 --> 01:05:47.100
It's fine for that particular
problem.

01:05:47.100 --> 01:05:49.470
But if that problem is embedded
in a bigger problem,

01:05:49.470 --> 01:05:52.020
you want to just know what the
answer's going to be roughly.

01:05:52.020 --> 01:05:54.430
So you can continue making
progress and decide should I

01:05:54.430 --> 01:05:56.430
go this route or this route.

01:05:56.430 --> 01:06:00.890
So that's why I'm not negative
on the standard ways.

01:06:00.890 --> 01:06:04.530
But I think the standard ways
are actually genuinely bad for

01:06:04.530 --> 01:06:06.490
problem solving in
new domains.

01:06:06.490 --> 01:06:10.610
And you want to augment your
perception so that you guide

01:06:10.610 --> 01:06:14.870
your search in the right
direction with big chunks.

01:06:14.870 --> 01:06:19.410
So that's fundamentally
important.

01:06:19.410 --> 01:06:22.180
So I think that was sort of
the main themes in the

01:06:22.180 --> 01:06:26.960
questions, and I'll look over
them and see which ones to

01:06:26.960 --> 01:06:29.880
answer probably at the beginning
of next time.

01:06:29.880 --> 01:06:33.410
I'll try to leave more time
for questions today, so we

01:06:33.410 --> 01:06:35.610
don't generate so many questions
next time to

01:06:35.610 --> 01:06:36.930
overflow it.

01:06:36.930 --> 01:06:42.200
OK, so before I continue, any
questions about these general

01:06:42.200 --> 01:06:44.140
principles of thinking
about your teaching?

01:06:48.470 --> 01:06:49.610
Yes?

01:06:49.610 --> 01:06:52.710
AUDIENCE: So the approach is
trying to focus more on the

01:06:52.710 --> 01:06:56.240
perceptual way to understand
thing, but on the other hand,

01:06:56.240 --> 01:06:58.550
the symbolic manipulations
are useful.

01:06:58.550 --> 01:07:03.060
So how do you make sure that the
students will themselves

01:07:03.060 --> 01:07:04.080
engage in the symbolic.

01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:09.240
How do you encourage them to
do the symbolic reasoning

01:07:09.240 --> 01:07:12.500
themselves without
scaring them?

01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:15.290
PROFESSOR: So how do you
encourage the students to do

01:07:15.290 --> 01:07:16.010
the symbolic reasoning?

01:07:16.010 --> 01:07:16.790
Because it is important.

01:07:16.790 --> 01:07:17.830
And I agree it is important.

01:07:17.830 --> 01:07:21.330
Just pure perception
isn't quite enough.

01:07:21.330 --> 01:07:24.900
I think most courses I would
say, and most teaching, is of

01:07:24.900 --> 01:07:27.970
99% symbolic and
1% perceptual.

01:07:27.970 --> 01:07:33.210
And it depends on the field,
but a rough estimate is I

01:07:33.210 --> 01:07:36.980
think it should be say something
like 20% symbolic

01:07:36.980 --> 01:07:40.160
and maybe 80% perceptual
initially.

01:07:40.160 --> 01:07:44.020
And then as you go to more and
more advanced levels, if

01:07:44.020 --> 01:07:47.270
you've done it mostly perceptual
earlier on, and

01:07:47.270 --> 01:07:49.380
you've developed the intuition,
then you can

01:07:49.380 --> 01:07:50.770
increase the amount
of symbolic.

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:52.700
So I think the way you do it
is you build it into the

01:07:52.700 --> 01:07:55.560
structure of the curriculum.

01:07:55.560 --> 01:07:58.300
So one particular course might
just have one mix.

01:07:58.300 --> 01:08:01.510
And the more advanced students
who got the perceptual

01:08:01.510 --> 01:08:05.070
material earlier are now
ready for the symbolic.

01:08:05.070 --> 01:08:10.620
So there's actually a graph
that I show for this.

01:08:21.890 --> 01:08:23.864
So that's the fraction
of symbolic.

01:08:31.430 --> 01:08:33.942
And that's the fraction of
perceptual material as you

01:08:33.942 --> 01:08:35.430
sort of go on in the major.

01:08:35.430 --> 01:08:38.819
So I think this is the ideal
structure for a major.

01:08:38.819 --> 01:08:42.220
Because this is going beyond
course design to whole design

01:08:42.220 --> 01:08:43.939
of a major in a curriculum.

01:08:43.939 --> 01:08:46.770
So early on, say for the
freshmen, it should be mostly

01:08:46.770 --> 01:08:48.220
perceptual.

01:08:48.220 --> 01:08:49.790
And there's many reasons
for that.

01:08:49.790 --> 01:08:52.529
First of all their symbolic
capacities--

01:08:52.529 --> 01:08:56.420
we're all bad at symbolic
capacities to start with.

01:08:56.420 --> 01:08:58.590
As freshmen, they're worse
than the seniors.

01:08:58.590 --> 01:09:00.800
They haven't had time for
example get sophisticated

01:09:00.800 --> 01:09:02.740
understanding of differential
equations.

01:09:02.740 --> 01:09:04.560
Their algebra's rusty.

01:09:04.560 --> 01:09:06.600
It's not really practiced
much.

01:09:06.600 --> 01:09:09.640
So don't rely on those
modes of learning.

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:11.290
Rely on the perceptual modes.

01:09:11.290 --> 01:09:14.069
And the perceptual modes give
you the big chunks.

01:09:14.069 --> 01:09:18.180
And so then once you have the
big chunks, well then sure

01:09:18.180 --> 01:09:20.220
they're ready for the symbolic
more and more.

01:09:20.220 --> 01:09:23.380
Because the symbolic fits into
the big chunks and helps guide

01:09:23.380 --> 01:09:24.760
the search.

01:09:24.760 --> 01:09:27.160
It helps actually
do the search.

01:09:27.160 --> 01:09:28.910
I have to calculate this.

01:09:28.910 --> 01:09:29.910
Then I calculate this.

01:09:29.910 --> 01:09:32.319
Well each calculation you do
you need the symbolic.

01:09:32.319 --> 01:09:34.550
So by the time they're graduate
students, hopefully

01:09:34.550 --> 01:09:36.700
the perceptual stuff they've
had it up here.

01:09:36.700 --> 01:09:37.729
It's really solid.

01:09:37.729 --> 01:09:40.160
And now they're ready for
partial differential equations

01:09:40.160 --> 01:09:41.439
and things like that.

01:09:41.439 --> 01:09:45.550
But earlier on, you don't
want to avoid partial

01:09:45.550 --> 01:09:46.310
differential equations.

01:09:46.310 --> 01:09:49.020
You want to solve them
in intuitive ways.

01:09:49.020 --> 01:09:54.300
And an example of that is early
on, when you're doing

01:09:54.300 --> 01:09:56.510
fluid mechanics, you would
solve the cones using

01:09:56.510 --> 01:09:59.130
dimensional analysis,
as we did before.

01:09:59.130 --> 01:10:01.390
You wouldn't solve the
Navier-Stokes equations.

01:10:01.390 --> 01:10:05.860
And later on, for example,
in a graduate class on

01:10:05.860 --> 01:10:08.920
computational fluid mechanics,
you'd actually try to simulate

01:10:08.920 --> 01:10:12.480
that and figure out what
the drag coefficient is

01:10:12.480 --> 01:10:13.830
numerically.

01:10:13.830 --> 01:10:16.420
So that's the mix between
perception and symbolic that I

01:10:16.420 --> 01:10:22.070
think is a very good way to
construct a whole curriculum.

01:10:22.070 --> 01:10:25.330
Does that answer
your question?

01:10:25.330 --> 01:10:26.580
OK.

